# Telegram bot token from @BotFather
BOT_TOKEN=your-bot-token-here

# Bot username WITHOUT the @ prefix.
# Required by the web dashboard's Telegram Login Widget.
# Must match the username registered with /setdomain in BotFather.
BOT_USERNAME=YukiBot

# Comma-separated list of Telegram user IDs that should have super-admin access.
# Super-admins see ALL chats in the dashboard with owner-level permissions.
# Find your ID by messaging @userinfobot on Telegram.
ADMIN_IDS=123456789,987654321

# MongoDB Atlas connection string
MONGODB_URI=mongodb+srv://user:pass@cluster.mongodb.net/yukibot?appName=yukibot

# JWT signing secret for the web dashboard.
# Generate with:  node -e "console.log(require('crypto').randomBytes(32).toString('hex'))"
JWT_SECRET=replace-me-with-a-64-char-hex-string

# HTTP port for the Express API + web dashboard.
# Railway sets PORT automatically; locally defaults to 3000.
PORT=3000

# Set to "false" to disable bot polling (useful when running migrations or local web-only dev)
BOT_ENABLED=true


How to use it

1. Create your web account (needs MONGODB_URI set in .env):

npm run cred:add -- <username> <yourTelegramId> <displayName>

It'll prompt for the password (no echo) twice. Min 8 chars. Example:

npm run cred:add -- dario 7669001456 "Dario"

Bind it to your real Telegram numeric ID — that's the one already on the Admin records, so you'll see exactly the chats you're admin in. If your ID is also in ADMIN_IDS env, you get super-admin powers (all chats), same as before.

2. List / remove

npm run cred:list
npm run cred:rm -- dario
